  <static seed="996" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/IdentifyAxisVertex90.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the axis of symmetry and vertex of the quadratic function.</p>
<p><m>{y}={4-2x^{2}}</m></p>
<p>Axis of symmetry: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p>Vertex: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x = 0</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,4\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This quadratic function is not given in standard form. First, we reorder the equation into standard form:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {y}={-2x^{2}+4} }</m></p>
<p>Now we can identify that:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ a=-2,b=0,c=4 }</m></p>
<p>To find the parabola<rsq/>s axis, we use the formula <m>\displaystyle{x=-\frac{b}{2a}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
  x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \\
    \amp = -\frac{0}{2(-2)} \\
    \amp = 0
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry is <m>\displaystyle{x=0}</m>.</p>
<p>Next, we substitute <m>\displaystyle{x=0}</m> into <m>\displaystyle{{y}={-2x^{2}+4}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = -2(0)^{2}+4 \\
    \amp = -2 \cdot 0 + 4 \\
    \amp = {4}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s vertex is <m>\displaystyle{(0,{4})}</m>.</p>
</solution>
